  "difficulty": "medium",
  "statement_md": "It is return day at the college library, and the counter is chaos. Every returned book carries a one-letter section code (`a` to `z`), and the books stand in a single row in the order they came in — written down, the row looks like a string of lowercase letters.\n\nThe librarian has exactly one move: whenever two books with the **same** code stand **directly next to each other**, she picks up that pair and shelves both. The books on either side of the gap slide together and become neighbours — which can create a brand-new matching pair.\n\nShe keeps making this move until no two neighbouring books share a code.\n\nPrint the row of codes that finally remains. If every single book gets shelved, print `EMPTY` instead.",
  "input_format_md": "The first line contains a single integer `T` — the number of test cases.\n\nFor each test case, a single line containing one string `S` of lowercase English letters — the row of section codes.",
  "output_format_md": "For each test case, print one line: the final row of codes after no more moves are possible, or `EMPTY` if no books remain.",
  "constraints_md": "- `1 ≤ T ≤ 10`\n- `1 ≤ |S| ≤ 2 × 10^4` for each test case\n- the total length of all strings in one input is at most `4 × 10^4`\n- `S` contains only lowercase English letters `a`–`z`",
